{{expand French|Cité du vin|category=Articles needing translation from French Wikipedia|date=March 2018}} The '''Cité du Vin''' is a [[museum]] as well as a place of exhibitions, shows, movie projections and [[Academia|academic]] [[seminar]]s on the theme of [[wine]] located in [[Bordeaux]], [[France]]. [[File:Cite du vin Bordeaux 2017 (37500642606).jpg|alt=Cité du Vin|thumb|Cité du Vin]]
== Construction == The cost of the construction has been underestimated. In January 2011, the cost of the construction had been estimated at 63 million euros excluding taxes.<ref name=lemoniteur>{{cite web |language=fr|date = 2 December 2014|title = Cité des civilisations du vin : un surcoût compensé par les retombées attendues|url = http://www.lemoniteur.fr/article/cite-des-civilisations-du-vin-un-surcout-compense-par-les-retombees-attendues-26571768|website=lemoniteur.fr}}</ref> But at the end of 2014, as the construction was in progress, the cost of the structure has been re-evaluated to reach 81,1 million euros excluding taxes.<ref name=lemoniteur />
== Opening == Its official opening by the [[President of France]] [[François Hollande]] and [[Alain Juppé]] took place on May 31, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |language=fr|date = 6 February 2016|title = L'entrée à 20 euros : tout ce qu'il faut savoir sur la Cité du vin de Bordeaux|url = http://www.sudouest.fr/2016/02/06/l-entree-a-20-euros-tout-ce-qu-il-faut-savoir-sur-la-cite-du-vin-de-bordeaux-2266324-6044.php|website=sudouest.fr}}</ref>
== Transportation == The Cité du Vin is accessible by tram (Line B which connects Berges de la Garonne to Pessac Center and France Alouette), by the ring road, by the Chaban-Delmas bridge and by lines 7 and 32 of the TBM network. A stop of the Batcub is located nearby.
